European inflation slumped on food
The acceleration of inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, with annual inflation of 3.1 percent after 2.6% in October, the European Union’s statistical office reported.
The official forecast is only 3 percent, according to Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, has not cut the base rate, saying that the reduction, together with rising commodity prices and easing unemployment, would lead to an inflation spiral.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but close to, 2%.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in its 22nd trap: “we need to talk down” inflation so that it does not have to act on this issue later.
In Germany, the November inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a 12-year record; in Spain, it rose to 4.1 percent from 3.6 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has been driven to high levels by rising food and energy prices.
Futures prices for wheat have risen by 88 percent, and soy prices have also reached their highest level since 1973.
There was also a substantial increase in the price of oil and dairy products in 2007.
The price of oil on the world market has increased by 52 percent this year, and last month it cost almost $100 a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but will fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
Analysts say the 12-month inflation rate will remain around 3 percent over the next 3-4 months, but the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, it is expected that the ECB has twice lowered interest rates during 2008.
Gallup sees a government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, Fidesz’s support has grown significantly by the beginning of December, so it now has the largest camp since 2002, while Gallup has never measured such low support for socialists at 13 percent.
In the case of certain party voters, the difference would mean more than two-thirds (71 percent) support against one-fifth (20 percent) support for MSZP due to the greater determination of the opposition voters.
According to the survey, the MDF and the SZDSZ are below the parliamentary threshold: their support within the total population is two percent.
Supporters in both camps are one percent more likely to vote.
The general economic mood, capable of reaching the previous low, has deteriorated further – never before has the proportion been so high, 41% of those who considered the country’s economic situation specifically very bad, while another 46% think the situation is quite bad.
After the more hopeful prospects of spring and summer, families are now again more pessimistic about the changes in their own financial situation.
For the next year, a larger half of the population expects further deterioration and only a tenth improvement.
In December, more people than in any previous Gallup poll, 71 percent, believed that the prime minister was doing his job poorly than well.
In Ferenc Gyurcsány, 13 percent of the respondents trust or very much trust, while in Viktor Orbán, 38 percent of the respondents are supporters.
54 per cent do not trust the prime minister at all, while 27 per cent do not trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the political situation is how much of society thinks that it is possible to deal with dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister without a change of government.
While after the riots in October last year, 35 per cent considered it desirable for the government and the Prime Minister to remain, at present this rate is only 20 per cent, while the relative majority (33 per cent) see the solution only in calling new elections.
Typical of the interest in the referendum, 60 percent of the respondents answered that they would definitely leave, and another 20 percent said that they would probably leave.
By way of comparison, only 55 percent would be certain to participate in a “parliamentary election this Sunday” and an additional 15 percent would consider their participation likely.
74 percent would say no to tuition, 79 percent would say no to visits, and 84 percent would say no to hospital fees.
If we look at the same proportions only among those who promise their participation in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of the voters would reject the introduction of tuition fees, visitation fees and hospital daily allowances.
The most expensive is Auchan, Tesco raised by almost a fifth
