Compared to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15 percent, while Tesco and Auchan increased the prices in the Daily’s basket by 18-18 percent.
Compared to last year’s most expensive and this year’s cheapest basket value, the difference was 12 percent, while last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket value grew by 21 percent.
The average increase in forint was 1480.
Last year, the average price increase came to HUF 1,206, so that last Christmas the VAT increase had an impact on prices.
It was precisely this process that disrupted trade, and apparently the stores were unable to decide how much margin to apply to a product, as they were unable to calculate the effect that price changes would have on consumption.
(If the turnover rate of a product is wrongly planned by the trader, then a significant profit can be made on the margin adjusted to traffic intensity.)
Due to VAT, the price increase of the Daily’s basket last year was so extreme that the most expensive basket was HUF 1,720 more than in 2006, while the price difference at the cheapest basket was only HUF 844.
This year, this extreme did not show itself, as the most expensive one this year was HUF 1630 more than last year, and the cheapest one also became more expensive by HUF 1284.
Compared to the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months, daily consumer goods became more than 30 percent more expensive in hypermarkets.
(By the way, this does not necessarily confirm the data of the HCSO: for some basic foods, the Statistical Office recorded a price increase of more than 30 percent over a period of 12 months.
For example, in the case of eggs.)
