They save on disinfectants in many places
This year, more than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
Hygiene conditions in hospitals, bed-crowding, and staff overload are not conducive to stopping infections, according to the chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
They also save on disinfectants in many places.
Recently, I was diagnosed with MRSA at the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
A man who was admitted after a serious accident was found to have bacteria resistant to antibiotics.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred earlier this year.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but soon after, he had to return home with an MRSA infection, and an important surgery has not yet been performed because of the bacteria in his body.
By December 10, 1,094 hospital-acquired infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens had been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, head of department at the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that infections caused by so many multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, the rest is unknown.
About two-thirds (683 infections) of the infections were caused by MRSA, a type of Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried in the nose by one-third of people without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. pharyngitis, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, a bacteria that responds well to antibiotics will develop into a highly antibiotic-resistant bacterium, which will spread rapidly in inappropriate hospital settings.
In particular, if the immune system is temporarily or permanently impaired, it can cause serious hospital-acquired infections, such as wound infections or sepsis, in patients with a weakened body, the elderly or low body weight.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections are part of the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is just not there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not tested.
Resistant to antibiotics
“Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff provides the patient with rubber gloves and masks, and we have the right antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients who are admitted to the hospital will be tested for MRSA in the first place, but it is not always possible to avoid infection.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of hospital-acquired infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current domestic hospital conditions are not favourable for preventing the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz says.
As this infection typically occurs in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor incoming patients and isolate MRSA-carrying patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
The National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these tests.
Most cases will come to light if the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the chief physician of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent the development of resistance to medicines, but this is not always the case in hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and primary care, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz said.
They save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted from one patient to another through the mediation of medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of gloves, masks play a very large role, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by contact, but in domestic hospital conditions it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, the wards are often crowded, and the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 metres apart.
Unfortunately, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz noted that hospitals in a poor financial situation save on disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients, so the chances of developing infections are even higher.
According to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, where the appropriate precautions are taken, there is less evidence of such an infection or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Programme against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA is a huge expense for health insurers, and they are fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, the government programme included the prevention and reduction of the incidence of MRSA.
The programme seems to have been successful, and according to the data provided, MRSA infections are on a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) includes among its priorities the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital-acquired infections caused by such pathogens.
