Another €400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three credit facility agreements worth a total of €400 million in support of education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy in Budapest on Friday.
The European Development Bank (EDB) approved a EUR 300 million budget for Hungary’s transport and environment projects under the Cohesion Fund in 2006, of which the parties have already signed a loan agreement of EUR 100 million, and the contract now signed is for the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
A 150 million euro loan agreement will also be used to finance education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary for this purpose, and the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later, by extending the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the parties signed a 50 million euro contract, which is primarily used for the research and development project of the University of Debrecen.
There was also talk of Metro 4.
They agreed that when Hungary finalises the details of the financing of the metro with the EU, they will return to the question of whether and how the original contract should be amended.
According to Janos Veres, this will take place in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of EUR 8.4 billion of 113 projects in Hungary.
The interest rate on the loans is linked to EURIBOR with a grace period of 8 years and is provided by the EIB without an availability commission.
Bulgaria is the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is amazing - the attention of the whole of Europe is focused on the previously little-mentioned Balkan country.
What, where and who are buying in the EU’s still cheapest but fast-expensive market?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The most popular property shopping destination in Eastern Europe right now is without a doubt Bulgaria, with cheap ski apartments and beach houses.
Among the mountains, the most fashionable are the areas of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa, and on the coast Albena, the "Golden Coast", the "Sun Beach", the ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for real estate in the area of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the central part of the country will also attract the interest of investors - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - and more and more people are shopping around the extremely cheap Russ, too.
The capital, Sofia, also offers attractive opportunities, with commercial and office spaces offering the highest return on investment.
Bulgaria is on the right track to become one of the most attractive European golf paradises, making it a top destination for the other two seasons in addition to the summer and winter seasons.
As a result, forward-thinking investors are already making big purchases, for example in the area around Bansko.
According to analysts, real estate buyers in Bulgaria are also seeking to change their lives and lifestyles.
Most of the customers are English, but they come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, and there are traditionally many Russian customers in the Black Sea and ski resorts.
Foreign buyers can be divided into three groups, says Georgy Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Settlers either buy renovated properties for between 50,000 and 100,000 euros, or run-down old houses for between 5,000 and 15,000 euros, and then renovate them.
They need good accessibility and communication opportunities, it is important for them to have a big city, shops and the proximity of the local doctor in general.
The second category belongs to holiday buyers (Bulgaria was included in the list of the top 10 German holiday destinations in December).
The third group is made up of business investors who buy in the hope of medium- to long-term value growth.
The price of real estate in the capital is constantly increasing, as demand is increasing.
Bulgaria has one of the lowest house prices in the European Union, but has risen by 21% per year over the past five years.
The rise in real estate prices substantially exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Water Affairs, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations on the post-2012 international climate regime will continue with the ministers.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which provides for efforts to follow the emissions reduction period set by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
This is currently under intense debate between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also indicated that it does not currently want to negotiate precise figures, although it is inclined to agree to a 25-40% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared to 1990.
Another big question at the conference is whether developed countries will commit not only to reducing emissions, but also to providing both material and technological assistance to countries in need.
There was also agreement on aid for developing countries.
The fund, which is provided for under the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member Governing Board, expected to be part of the United Nations Global Environment Facility (GEF).
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Water Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to preserve its flagship role in global climate protection efforts and to facilitate the creation of a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to a 20% reduction in its greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the “post-2012 agreement”, and is ready to commit to a 30% reduction if other large developed regions of the world and developing countries are willing to assume their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor referred to the fact that in 1997 the countries that acceded to the Kyoto Protocol set an overall reduction target of 5.2 percent, within which the EU – then 15 member states – undertook minus 8 percent.
Hungary’s obligation is a 6 percent reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to the period 1985-87, which Hungary will meet.
The stakes are high in Bali, as the long-term international climate policy agreement must be concluded within two years, otherwise its entry into force would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by another international emission reduction system, which the latest UN scientific body for climate change, the IPCC, Nobel Peace Prize winner, pointed out as necessary.
This would delay emission reductions and make it inevitable to increase the global average temperature by more than 2 degrees Celsius, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British army recruits on YouTube
Footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan will be posted on the video sharing platform by British military units to promote themselves.
The British Air Force (RAF) was the first to post videos on YouTube: special forces in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban since March 2006.
These miniature helmet-mounted cameras are checked at the Air Force’s operation headquarters in Kandahar and sent to London, where they are uploaded to the Internet by the locals.
The Political Message is Inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already posted 139 videos on the Internet, and their “channel” has been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and publishes videos of actions in both Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Commonwealth Office and Iraq's International Peacekeeping Forces (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Missions in Afghanistan
The Air Force originally intended the videos to be used for recruitment purposes, and the Defense Ministry said it was also good for informing the public about the real purpose of the military’s presence abroad.
Propaganda in this form costs almost nothing compared to traditional TV recruitment ads, defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but it inevitably carries some political message as well, as it certifies the validity of military actions decided by the government in a specific form.
The Americans played a game.
The military also has a problem with the fact that in addition to the carefully edited, censored footage, amateur videos are also being shared, which, for example, show the deaths of soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the officers talk only about the losses, but do not show the bloody side of the fight.
Several videos from the Iraq and Afghanistan theatres have already been posted on the internet, but the British military has only recently received them.
Americans recruit in a slightly different way with the free-to-download shooter America's Army, in which players can take on the role of soldiers in a more or less lifelike simulation.
