Political Capital: the Hungarian Guard increased the country’s risk
The activity of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August this year with the support of the Jobbik Movement for Hungary, increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital.
In the company’s “risk warning”, they wrote that the greatest political risk in connection with the activity of the Hungarian Guard is that “by exacerbating the already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Roma population in Hungary, violent ethnic clashes may already develop in the short term”.
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is presumably aimed at provoking such an act, the research institute added.
“The public debate on the Roma issue was left to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who were able to build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian antagonism,” the statement said.
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflict, they say.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard “have significantly worsened the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of the belief in the country’s stability and democratic development”, due to the large amount of domestic and international media attention.
It is recalled that since the autumn of 2006 radical and far-right groups in Hungary have gained increasing publicity and momentum as a result of the reorganization of several organizations calling themselves “national self-defence” associations that have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007.
“The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil organizations, while openly proclaiming the preparation of their members – even armed ones – for defence (disaster protection, defence, law enforcement) tasks, moreover, citing the incompetence of the police, the army, i.e. the state,” they added.
They noted that this is done in accordance with a method that seeks to put different political aspirations into civilian clothes based on the anti-political and anti-party nature of society.
The emphasis on civility and the form of the association is not only meant to avoid the legal pitfalls of court registration in the case of these associations, but also serves as a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk-increasing factor in terms of neighbourhood relations.
“In recent months, several neighbouring countries have referred to the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of danger, while ultranationalist political figures in some neighbouring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
All this affects the political stability of the region,” they added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in East-Central Europe, so political risks have increased for the region as a whole.
The operation of the Hungarian Guard is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
The formation of the Bulgarian Guard is due to the mass riots of the Roma in one of the districts of Sofia (Krasna Polyana).
