In Hungary, the red-letter days are clearly marked by the law, and it has become common practice to rearrange workdays around the holidays, which will be reduced next year.
There is no uniform celebration in the United States and the United States.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and public holidays.
Public holidays are mostly associated with church holidays and significant historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year here: the last day of the old year and the first day of the new one are both holidays - the latter for the rest of the New Year's Eve.
We have a total of 11 red-letter holidays throughout the year.
The 15th of March and the 23rd of October, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, are also national holidays.
On the 20th of August we celebrate the foundation of the state, on the 1st of May we celebrate the work, and on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, we celebrate Easter, Pentecost and Christmas on two days.
Since our state, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on the weekends according to the calendar, it has become common practice to transfer workdays in cases where we would only work one day before or after the red-letter holiday.
True, the price of extended weekends is that we do not stay away from work and school on the previous Saturdays.
The exact time of the day immediately before or after the holiday is regulated by a separate decree of the Minister of Labour for many years.
The law applies to all employers and their employees, civil servants and public service employees alike.
However, it does not affect service companies and institutions operating without interruption and operating on public holidays due to their intended purpose.
This year, the work schedule will only change around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life in the country will almost stop, since, according to experience, the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve will be "slipped" by the majority of people, or they will use their saved holidays for this purpose.
Next year we will have several holidays in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be less workday relocations than this year.
First, the calendar changes around the work day, so that employees can stay at home for four consecutive days.
Saturday, April 26, will be a working day, in exchange for Friday, May 2, being a day of rest.
The second relocation is related to the October 23 holiday: on Saturday, October 18th, you will have to work instead of Friday, October 24th.
The end of the year, however, can be spent in the spirit of the holiday next year, as from December 24, almost everywhere there will be a nonstop break, even if the New Year’s Eve falls on Wednesday.
6 little things you can do to annoy your colleagues
Emails we forget to send, voicemail messages we never get, innocent lies we almost don’t even notice: they “color” the everyday life at work.
The question is whether you get used to small inconveniences or put on the gloves and consciously avoid ambiguous situations that cause annoyance to others.
Tips.
“Sorry, I forgot to tell you that you were looking for me in the marketing department,” one of your colleagues said.
That you missed a meeting because of that?
At best, he’ll apologize and try to make up for it, perhaps calling the marketing department to tell you he forgot to deliver the message (this is the less-ordinary solution).
Most of the time, it's done with an apology.
Before you make an embarrassing apology, it’s worth thinking about what you can do to make your colleagues feel uncomfortable and make a conscious effort to avoid it.
Are you borrowing something that doesn’t belong to you?
There's nothing more annoying than reaching for a piece of paper, stationery, or your phone, and it's nowhere to be found.
Do you remember yesterday you put your stapler on the table, but it took off in the morning?
Do you find your lost pen on a colleague’s desk?
Do not take anything from your colleagues without asking, because they will rightly be angry at you for stealing their property.
Don’t put office envelopes or post-it in your pocket, because it can be unpleasant if it runs out before your time and you need it immediately.
Are you gossiping about your colleagues' personal lives?
There is no good way to stop the rumors that are already spreading.
Who, who, what did he do?
Where and why?
Don’t tell everyone about your colleagues’ private life.
If one of them shares their deepest secrets with you, don’t abuse their trust.
Bury what you hear, and do not discuss it with your colleagues in your absence, even if others know about your colleague’s conduct.
Unjustifiably report sick?
When you call the office and report a splitting headache because you feel unwell or you feel you would rather rest that day; remember that your work, your urgent tasks, your deadline work must be done by someone else for you.
Don’t mess with your colleagues.
If you know in advance that you won’t be going to the office the next day, or that something might come up that will force you to stay at home, let your colleagues and bosses know that you won’t be missing them the next day.
growl, giggle, phone call
You get into the work, but you get dragged out of it by the giggles of your colleagues?
Have you unwittingly overheard a phone conversation that would have been better left unheard?
Do not disturb your co-workers with humming, singing, loud talking (which you do over their heads), nor with beating feet, constant swearing, loud discontent.
All of these can be confusing, even if they are not involved in a project (writing, planning, organizing).
Do you blame others for your mistakes?
If you don’t have something in time, you forgot to send an important letter or message, don’t blame others for your forgetfulness!
Don't refer to the chaos in the office, your noisy colleagues.
Admit when you have made a mistake and someone else has suffered a disadvantage, and eliminate the damage.
Ask yourself how you can make up for your mistake and make up for your failure.
Do you feel at home in the office?
Bear pants and slippers: comfortable to wear at home, but not in the office!
Don’t wear comfortable clothes even if your job allows it.
Don’t be sloppy, respect your colleagues and yourself by wearing ordinary clothes – if your job demands it, pretty and elegant – to go to the office!
