Depressing Memories
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Bad Arolsen archive, which documents the fate of 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime, has been made public.
The 47 million archival documents, which occupy 27 kilometres of shelves in Bad Arolsen in the Hessen province, have so far only been searchable for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. providing only unique and anonymous access to the victims or their descendants.
In May 2006, the eleven states that manage the archives, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to open the archive to researchers and historians.
After all the states ratified the treaty, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the archives in Bad Arolsen allows historians to conduct research on “the relocation of prisoners, the residents of the camps and the state of health of the forced laborers,” explains Reto Meistern, director of the archive managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, have opposed the disclosure of the documents because they contain names and thus confidential information.
These include, for example, the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deported victims.
The lists of concentration camps and the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo began to be collected after the war for practical reasons, the purpose being to search for civilians who had been deported or sentenced to forced labour, and possibly to provide evidence of their internment, on the basis of which they could receive compensation.
In Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are already processing tens of thousands of individual needs.
However, some members of the scientific community do not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive to be of paramount importance.
“These documents basically contain nothing new,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the research center for antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin.
