Congress approves takeover of MiFID, which took effect on November 1
In parallel with parliamentary proceedings, which ended today with a vote in Congress approving the Senate amendments, the government has initiated a social dialogue on the underlying legislation so that both can enter into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the various groups unanimously highlighted the efforts of representatives and senators in negotiations and agreements, which served to develop the most favourable normative for protecting investors, as well as the detailed regulation of the companies’ activities in order to ensure efficient market operation.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Act, will allow for the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, broadening the supervisory powers of the Spanish National Securities Markets Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between different supervisors in the European Union.
The new directive will allow financial advisory services to be provided to specialised firms, but also to natural or legal persons, and will create a new form of financial services company (ESIS), namely financial advisory companies (AFI), in addition to securities trading companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the Act increases the number of systems capable of executing operations involving funds, thus adding to the regulated secondary markets the multilateral trading platforms and the internalisation systems for the execution of orders, which are in competition with the current stock exchange participants.
In addition, the Act requires investment service providers to provide market information on the determining aspects of their business profile, risk-taking and risk management methods, and to keep a record of all operations carried out in order to facilitate control of the CNMV.
The Congressional Economic Commission has introduced a number of amendments. Of particular importance is that securitised debt is treated as a “complex” asset because of its high risk to the investor. This has been proven in connection with US high-risk mortgage lending (subprime).
On the other hand, the transposition of the directive was also used to legally outline the range of activities of those with economic and entrepreneurial qualifications, 30 years after the Royal Decree defining professional functions that can only be carried out by economists came into force in 1977.
And the Senate has proposed the creation of new players in the financial sector, such as an intermediary agent who works for someone else’s account, does not need CNMV’s permission, and can sell products or acquire clients to several investment companies at the same time.
The Consumer Price Index increased by 0.5 points in November, reaching 4.1%.
This indicator, taken into account by Eurostat for the calculation of the inflation rate in the European Union, shows the evolution of prices in Spain for the month of November.
Its publication is in line with the strategy of Eurostat and the European Central Bank to provide data that are comparable with data from the United States, both in terms of time of production and nature.
For the preliminary indicator, the same calculation method is used as for the calculation of the Harmonised Price Index, but the statistical modelling method differs in estimating the information that is not yet available at the time of disclosure.
The Statistical Office pointed out that the preliminary indicator is purely indicative and therefore may differ from the final data, which will be published on 14 December.
"The Consumer Price Index remains relatively high."
Pedro Solbes, a vice-president of the government and Minister of Economic Affairs, said that the increase in the Consumer Price Index to 4.1% in November was only "temporary in nature", but at the same time predicted that the price index is expected to remain "relatively high" in the coming months.
In Parliament's corridors, Solbes confirmed that "although the indicator is not very favourable", the inflation rate in Spain within the monetary union has remained more or less at the same level in recent years.
He added that the month of November brought “less surprises” than the previous month, when the Government did not expect such a large increase.
"We were expecting a value of around 4%," the Minister of Economic Affairs acknowledged in connection with the data published today.
