Further concerns about the Russian-Ukrainian gas dispute
The gas price dispute between Ukraine and Russia has been renewed, which may also affect Russian fuel to be transported to Western Europe.
Most of the Russian gas exported to the European Union (EU) is transported through Ukraine, and the disputes between the two nations are always receiving a great deal of attention.
Kiev has said that if Moscow raises the price of gas paid by Ukrainians, they will also impose higher transit costs on Russia.
An earlier dispute between the two countries last year resulted in a reduction in supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow is between the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned natural gas monopoly Gazprom over an attempt to reach an agreement on the price of gas that Ukraine will pay to Russia in 2008.
Gazprom has stated that it will have to implement a 50% increase in gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan compared to the price agreement with Ukraine for 2008.
According to analysts, this could mean a 40% increase in the price of shipments from Gazprom for Ukraine.
“It is important that during the negotiations, we argue in accordance with one of the most important transit countries for natural gas,” Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinah told Reuters.
“The changes in gas prices should definitely be linked to our discussion on the cost of transit through Ukraine (and into Western Europe),” he said.
As a result of the recent major gas flood between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom shut down the gas pipeline to Ukraine in January 2006.
This resulted in a domino-like decline in exports to Western Europe, which also pushed up prices to a large extent.
A quarter of the EU’s gas supply comes from Russia.
Russia has the largest natural gas reserves in the world, but most of them are still undiscovered.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own gas supply with natural gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet states in Central Asia.
NHS ‘required to check on foreign workers’
Scottish NHS committees should improve criminal records checks for workers from outside Europe, a supervisory body said.
The proposal was put forward by chief accountant Robert Black after a foreign doctor in Scotland was linked to the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland does not have accurate figures on the number of employees overseas.
At the same time, its report, through a sample of five health authorities, also identified key controls that had been properly implemented.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the chief accountant checked the list of employees recruited outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullah, a 28-year-old Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep crashed into the main terminal of the building.
Abdullah was one of three doctors who were interrogated by the Old Bailey Court via video link in October on charges of attempted car bombings in the United Kingdom.
NHS committees should check the qualifications and work experience of their overseas employees before they start work, as well as their availability with the necessary permits to work in the UK.
Although the Scottish Health Commissions use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency is not authorized to obtain such information from outside the UK.
Among other things, the report of the Chief Auditor suggested that the committees introduce a guide for the Criminal Records Bureau, which would facilitate the control processes of the employer with the various overseas countries.
“Although we found evidence of such checks in staff records, they are not systematically carried out,” the report states.
According to Black, although the Scottish NHS performs its own pre-employment screening process at a high level, he added: “Our report highlights areas for improvement in the system so that we have up-to-date information on the number of NHS staff coming from overseas.”
Dr Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks could be used to identify potential NHS employees who might commit terrorist acts in the future.
“According to the report, the pre-employment checks currently in place in the NHS Scotland are working well and the value of the proposals is not yet transparent,” he added.
According to Scottish health authorities, the current number of their overseas staff, mostly doctors and nurses, is 1,161.
However, the main accountant pointed out that the figures are likely to be higher, which is partly explained by the difficulties the committees have in identifying staff on indefinite leave.
The investigation also showed that the inspection procedures in the Ayrshire and Arran area, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and the NHS authorities in Lothian are largely harmonised.
These procedures included checks on passports, work permits and qualification papers.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing a policy and guidance on pre-employment checks for NHS employees from overseas.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I am delighted that this mission has been carried out following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
He added that the Scottish Government, in cooperation with the Health Committees, will take into account the proposals in the report and ensure that the up-to-date guidance on pre-employment checks for the entire staff, including those from overseas, reflects best practice. The updated version is planned to be published next month.
Joy Division at the Film Awards
Joy Division's biopic of late singer Ian Curtis, "Control", won five awards at the British Independent Film Awards, including Best Picture.
The award went to Sam Riley, who worked in a warehouse before playing Curtis, as well as director Anton Corbijn and supporting actor Toby Kebbell.
Dame Judi Dench won the award for Best Actress for the thriller "Details of a Scandal."
The Variety Award was won by Daniel Craig, who played Bond, for putting British film in the international spotlight.
The awards were presented at a ceremony at the Roundhouse in London.
The film "Control" chronicles Curtis' rise to prominence within Joy Division until 1980, when he committed suicide at the age of 23.
The Black and White film, featuring "The Killers", "David Bowie" and "New Order on the soundtrack", cost just <0xC2><0xA3>3 million to make.
Dutch photographer Corbijn, who had previously been known for creating the album cover for U2's "Joshua Tree", won two awards: Best Director and Best Beginner Director.
Another award winner of the ceremony focused on rock music; Julien Temple's film about Joe Strummer, the singer of Clash, won the award for best documentary.
The award for Best Actor went to Viggo Mortensen for his role as David Cronenberg in the London-based crime thriller The Killer Promises.
Ray Winstone, famous for his tough-guy roles, received the Richard Harris Award for Outstanding Contribution to the British Film Industry.
The 50-year-old actor, who has made films such as "Scum", "Ehkoppon" and "Sexy Dog", is currently working on the film "Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull".
Winstone is proud to receive the award named after the star of "Camelot" and "Harry Potter" Harris, who died in 2002.
“For people like me, people like Richard Harris and Albert Finney have opened the door,” Winstone said.
“I feel really lucky to have had the opportunity to meet Richard Harris several times.
"Richard Harris' style is close to my heart, he was a great actor of his time and I respect him very much."
The selection of independent film awards, known as Bifa, is decided by a group of film directors, actors and festival organisers.
Bifa supporters and patrons include Mike Figgis, Ken Loach, Ewan McGregor, Samantha Morton, Bill Nighy, Meera Syal and Michael Winterbottom.
