Is the second-market mortgage market crisis threatening America’s credit card market?
When blood gets into the water, it’s natural for sharks to appear nearby.
Now that the U.S. housing market is failing, predators are focusing on the country’s credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs believe that if the mortgage crisis infects other forms of consumer credit, the credit card market could lose up to $99 billion.
The signs of tension are clearly visible.
There was an increase in both the write-off rate for non-recoverable loans and the default rate for overdue payments over 30 days.
HSBC reported a $1.4 billion loss in the U.S. consumer finance segment last month, in part due to the financial weakness of cardholders.
However, the panic is still too early.
The ratio of write-offs and late payments remains low.
Moody's has a late-payment ratio of 3.89% for the third quarter, which is one full percentage point lower than the historical average.
The decrease in the rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
The change in the US rules on individual insolvency in 2005 has led to a sharp decrease in the number of people filing for insolvency, but at the same time has led to large losses in the credit card market; the number of bankruptcy petitions (and thus the write-off rate) is expected to increase again, regardless of whether the conditions for borrowing as a whole are deteriorating or not.
The payment rate, which shows the ratio of monthly credit repayments to consumers, is also solid in the market.
In addition, confidence in credit card-backed securities is quite strong, despite the paralysis in other areas of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup Research estimates that the volume of emissions in 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
The signs of the impact of the mortgage crisis on the credit card market are clear: consumers are accumulating credit card debt to repay home loans.
At the same time, card issuers primarily monitor financial flows and not asset values, so a fall in house prices does not necessarily cause a change in the creditworthiness of borrowers.
Creditors may also benefit from the situation.
If the property is worth less than the value of the mortgage loan, the incentive for consumers to pay off the loan is reduced; as a result, the repayment of debts on credit cards is promoted in the priority ranking.
By changing interest rates or lending limits, card issuers can adapt to changing conditions more quickly and flexibly than mortgage lenders.
Theoretically, this should reduce the risk of sudden repricing of assets.
“It’s unlikely that we’ll wake up one day to completely revalue our loans,” said Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
If a subprime-like sudden crisis in the credit card market is less likely, the risk of a gradual decline is much higher.
