Venus is Earth's evil twin.
Despite the harsh atmosphere of Venus, it is more similar to Earth than previously thought: In its atmosphere, the European Venus Express spacecraft has discovered lightning strikes, and in its polar orbits, wind vortices similar to those that occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that Venus is lightning.
The European “Venus Express” spacecraft has provided evidence – it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus spreads from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 56 kilometers, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, on the pages of the science magazine “Nature”.
According to the famous "primitive soup theory", the formation of life on Earth was caused by lightning: According to the theory, thunderstorms triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early times," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
At present, there can hardly be a living organism on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures sometimes reach 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's hellish twin, but it's still Earth's twin," Russell said.
The main question of the Esa mission is why Venus, so similar in mass and size to Earth, is on a completely different path of evolution.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone in the exploration of Venus, because no probe has been on its way to find this planet since the early 1990s.
The latest findings, already presented in several "Nature" papers, are not only proving the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system, according to the researchers.
"They also point out that the resemblance of the neighboring planet to Earth is greater than we first assumed," Esa said.
In addition to the well-known North Pole cyclone, the researchers also discovered a much faster moving cloud vortex at the South Pole.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth’s winter hemisphere, according to a team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica in Italy.
The second innermost planet in the solar system is almost the same mass as Earth, and with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, it is almost the size of Earth.
The star, also known as the Morning Star, orbits the Sun in less than 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly around its own axis: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus’ surface temperature, combined with a pressure of 92 bar, barely resembles Earth’s, scientists assume that both planets formed under completely similar conditions.
Both of them accumulated water, which remained on Earth as an ocean, while on Venus it left for the universe.
And while on Earth carbon dioxide is bound in carbonate rocks, on Venus it forms a large part of the atmosphere.
