Richard Gere is not a cynic.
Through "Hunting" and "M<0xC3><0xB6>rderischer Frieden" again two films deal with the Balkan war.
But none of them are convincing.
The basic idea is either too focused on action and shooting, or too sentimental.
Even Richard Gere can't help you with that in "Hunting."
First, the good news: Although the two war criminals, Karadzic and Mladic, are still hiding in the Balkan mountains, they found the actor Richard Gere there, in the dark background of the Bosnian war.
Lately, we’ve lost sight of the most beautiful man of the eighties, because of his many good-for-nothing roles in emotional films for women and the many press conferences on the subject of Buddhism.
And suddenly, Richard Gere is the most compelling reason to watch "Hunting" after all.
In essence, the war correspondent Simon Hunt is exactly what Gere would have been if fate and the film industry had not been so kind to him: A man who had long since left his best years behind him, but whose decline has preserved much of its former charm as a ruinous monument.
