While it is to be welcomed that, for once, Serbs are not portrayed as the sole cause of all evil, the film, which carries the shallowness of TV films, is too quickly lost in shootings and eventful scenes.
"Cobra 11" carries the character of a war instead of a highway.
On the other hand, in the case of "Hunting", it can be examined as an example why not a single really good film has been made about the Balkan war.
The story of three U.S. war correspondents who set out to find the Serbian war criminal known as "The Fox" with a different director, a different screenwriter (both in Richard Shepard's personal union) might have turned into a new "Apocalypse Now" at another time.
The stories have a surprising resemblance: In both cases, small groups set off into the forest to accomplish what the military can’t—and in both cases, it’s a maddening journey.
One of the reasons for the fall of “Hunting” is that he simply won’t let Simon Hunt be the depraved cynic he first introduces him to.
No, and in the script, he even spends a romantic relationship with a Muslim Bosnian woman who was later murdered.
“Hunting” slips away when reporters in the last five minutes of the film achieve what NATO, the CIA and all the bounty hunters around the world have failed to do in five years: capture the war criminal and then hand him over to the Muslim Bosnians for just revenge.
This is so bad that one would prefer to go to the International Criminal Court in The Hague for a crime against the logic of cinema.
The purpose of the film is deeply human.
He intends to discredit the fact that Karadzic and Mladic are still at large, and accuses the Americans and the French (who are supposedly still exceptionally united) of not pursuing the persecution intensively enough because of secret political bargaining.
But sometimes good and evil are so similar that you think of a famous Brecht poem.
In it, the poet writes of a wooden mask depicting an Asian demon on his desk: "I gaze intently at the bulging vein in his temple, which betrays how tiring it is to be bad."
Films like "Hunting" have the same oversized, human-headed masks that show how tiring it is to be good.
This problem is not limited to the genre of films about the war in the Balkans.
Recently, it was reported in the newspaper that all the Hollywood films about Iraq were a failure.
We can add: There is not a single good film about South Africa yet.
It’s almost always true: when a star roams the world’s hotspots or minefields, it turns out to be something like “On the Paths of Freedom” with Patricia Arquette, “Without Borders” with Angelina Jolie, or “Blood Diamond” with Leonardo Di Caprio.
It is possible that these conflicts are simply too close in time.
After all, it was decades before Hollywood was able to make a good film about the Holocaust with the film "Schindler's List."
There are probably a few films left to make, as the classic films about the Vietnam War, such as "The Deer Hunter", "Apocalypse Now" or "Full Metal Jacket" were not universally celebrated as masterpieces in their day.
But it’s possible that today, when all the mass killings arrive in our homes in real time, right through two screens, we simply know too much about the world’s conflicts.
And it robs screenwriters of the reality of ignoring what it would take to tell good stories.
After all, “To Be or Not to Be” or “The Dictator” was so successful because Lubitsch and Chaplin did not yet know how terrible the Nazi regime really was.
Maybe you shouldn't pursue the good if you want to make a good movie.
